<BlogLayout
  title="I Started a Fabrication Company in an RV"
  description="The real origin story of 3D3D . a generator, a 30-year-old motorhome, $30/day in gas, and a lot of things catching fire."
  datePublished="2025-05-02"
  author="Ken"
>
  <h2>It Wasn't a Plan</h2>

  <p>
    Nobody sits down and says, "I'm going to start a specialty fabrication company out of a Class A motorhome from the '90s." That's not a business plan. That's what happens when you're stubborn, broke, and too deep into an idea to turn back.
  </p>

  <p>
    I'd been a mechanic for a decade. Good at it. Burned out on it. I started tinkering with 3D printers because I kept running into the same problem in the shop, parts that didn't exist anymore, brackets that should exist but don't, custom mounts that nobody sells because the market is too small. I figured if I could make those things myself, other people needed them made too.
  </p>

  <h2>The RV</h2>

  <p>
    The motorhome was a 1993 something-or-other. It ran. Mostly. The generator worked, which was the important part, because that's what powered the printers. I had two machines running in the back, a laptop on the dinette, and filament rolls stored in every cabinet where normal people keep dishes.
  </p>

  <p>
    The generator burned through propane and gas like you wouldn't believe. Thirty dollars a day just to keep the lights on and the printers running. In the summer, the heat inside was unbearable, two printers running at 60-degree bed temps plus a generator plus Atlantic Canada humidity. I'd open every window and it still felt like working inside a clothes dryer.
  </p>

  <h2>Everything Broke</h2>

  <p>
    The generator died twice. The RV's house batteries gave up. A power surge took out a printer's mainboard. The water pump failed and I didn't notice until there was a puddle under the bed. The roof leaked onto a spool of PLA and ruined an entire kilogram of filament, which, when you're counting every dollar, feels like a personal attack.
  </p>

  <p>
    But the prints kept coming. Customers didn't know or care that their marine bracket was being printed in a motorhome parked behind a friend's shop. They cared that it showed up on time, fit perfectly, and survived saltwater. That part I could deliver.
  </p>

  <h2>Why It Worked</h2>

  <p>
    The RV wasn't a disadvantage. It was mobile. I could drive to a marina and print parts dockside. I could set up at a car meet and show people what these machines could do. I could relocate when the work moved. That flexibility turned into a core part of what 3D3D is today, we go where the problem is.
  </p>

  <p>
    Being broke also forced discipline. Every spool of filament had to earn its cost back. Every print had to be right the first time because I couldn't afford to waste material on failures. That mindset stuck. We still run lean, we still hate waste, and we still treat every gram of filament like it costs money, because it does.
  </p>

  <h2>Getting Out of the RV</h2>

  <p>
    Eventually the operation outgrew the motorhome. More printers, more orders, more materials to stock. I moved into a proper workspace. But I kept the mentality. Low overhead. No flash. Spend money on machines and materials, not on a fancy office nobody visits.
  </p>

  <p>
    People sometimes ask if I'm embarrassed about the RV days. Not even a little. That motorhome is where 3D3D learned to be scrappy, resourceful, and relentless. Every company has an origin story. Most of them are boring. Ours involves a generator fire and a melted spool of PETG. I'll take that.
  </p>

  <h2>What I'd Tell Someone Starting Out</h2>

  <p>
    You don't need a perfect setup. You need a machine that works, a skill that people will pay for, and the willingness to figure out the rest as you go. The RV taught me that. Start ugly. Get better. Ship parts.
  </p>
